data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false").

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use AreEqual for exact counts — gives "Expected:3, Actual:5" on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // CollectionAssert for collection-specific checks
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

    // Assert.IsTrue is fine for predicate checks, but use a message
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Use IsNotNull instead of wrapping in IsTrue
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin, "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, count)` or `CollectionAssert.That` | Exact expectation, clear failure message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Semantic clarity, better message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(a == b)` | `Assert.AreEqual(a, b)` | Shows expected vs actual on failure |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
- `AreEqual` / `AreNotEqual` — same elements, same order
- `AreEquivalent` — same elements, any order
- `Contains` / `DoesNotContain`
- `AllItemsAreInstancesOfType`
- `AllItemsAreUnique`
- `IsSubsetOf`

The general rule: use the **most specific assertion** available — you get better failure diagnostics for free.
